ing","tags":[],"url":"/docs/server/schema#users","content":"Users"},"1210":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-53","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/server/schema#get-user","content":"Get user"},"1211":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-54","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/server/schema#get-users","content":"Get users"},"1212":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-55","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/server/schema#create-user","content":"Create user"},"1213":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-56","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/server/schema#delete-user","content":"Delete user"},"1214":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-57","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/server/schema#update-user","content":"Update user"},"1215":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-58","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/server/schema#update-permissions","content":"Update permissions"},"1216":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-59","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/server/schema#change-password","content":"Change password"},"1217":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-60","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/server/schema#authentication","content":"Authentication"},"1218":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-61","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/server/schema#login-user","content":"Login user"},"1219":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-62","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/server/schema#logout-user","content":"Logout user"},"1220":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-63","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/server/schema#personal-access-tokens","content":"Personal access tokens"},"1221":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-64","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/server/schema#get-personal-access-tokens","content":"Get personal access tokens"},"1222":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-65","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/server/schema#create-personal-access-token","content":"Create personal access token"},"1223":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-66","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/server/schema#delete-personal-access-token","content":"Delete personal access token"},"1224":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-67","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/server/schema#login-with-personal-access-token","content":"Login with personal access token"},"1225":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-68","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/schema","content":"Since the Iggy server supports a variety of transport protocols, it is important to have a common schema for all of them, that will represent the data in a unified way. Commands (requests), responses, data models, status codes, must be the same for all transports."},"1226":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-69","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/schema","content":"Currently, there are 2 ways of data representation: JSON (text) and binary - any serialization format that you prefer such as bincode, SBE, flatbuffers, protobuf or even your custom one, as the server simply expects the raw bytes as the message payload."},"1227":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-70","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/schema","content":"The binary format is more compact and efficient, but it is not human-readable - it's being used by TCP and QUIC transports. The JSON format is used by HTTP transport - all the existing endpoints are available in the server.http."},"1228":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-71","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/schema","content":"All multi-byte integer fields use little-endian encoding throughout."},"1229":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-72","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/schema#request-schema","content":"All the requests are represented as a binary message. The message consists of 3 parts: length, code and payload:"},"1230":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-73","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/schema#request-schema","content":"length - 4-byte integer (u32) which represents the total length: code (4 bytes) + payload (N bytes)"},"1231":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-74","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/schema#request-schema","content":"code - 4-byte integer (u32) which represents the request code"},"1232":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-75","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/schema#request-schema","content":"payload - binary data of N bytes length"},"1233":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-76","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/schema#request-schema","content":"For example, if the payload is 100 bytes, the length will have a value of 104 (100 bytes for payload + 4 const bytes for the code). The message as whole will have 108 (4 + 4 + 100) bytes size."},"1234":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-77","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/schema#response-schema","content":"All the responses are represented as a binary message. The message consists of 3 parts: status, length and payload:"},"1235":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-78","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/schema#response-schema","content":"status - 4-byte integer (u32) which represents the status code. The status code is 0 for success and any other value for an error."},"1236":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-79","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/schema#response-schema","content":"length - 4-byte integer (u32) which represents the total length: status (4 bytes) + payload (N bytes)"},"1237":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-80","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/schema#response-schema","content":"payload - binary data of N bytes length"},"1238":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-81","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/schema#response-schema","content":"In case of errors, the length will be always equal to 0 and the payload will be empty."},"1239":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-82","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/schema#response-schema","content":"When trying to fetch the resource which may not exist, such as a stream, topic, user etc., the response will have a status code 0 (OK), but the payload will be empty, as there's no data to return."},"1240":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-83","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/schema#identifier","content":"The Identifier is a struct which represents the identifier of a stream, topic, user, or consumer group. It consists of the kind (numeric or string), length (length of the identifier value) and value (actual value of the identifier). The value is a vector of bytes, which can be either a numeric value (e.g. 1 encoded as const 4 bytes for u32 type) or a string (e.g. \"my-stream\") with variable length of UTF-8 string, maximum 255 bytes (chars)."},"1241":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-84","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/schema#identifier","content":"Serialization"},"1242":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-85","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/schema#identifier","content":"kind - 1 byte"},"1243":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-86","page_id":"/docs/server/schema","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/server/schema#identifier","content":"length - 1 byte"},"1244":{"id":"/docs/server/schema-87","page_id":"/docs/s