":["Documentation","Connectors","Sinks"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/quickwit"},"1772":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/quickwit-0","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/quickwit","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/quickwit#configuration","content":"Configuration"},"1773":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/quickwit-1","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/quickwit","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/quickwit","content":"The Quickwit connector allows you to send data to the Quickwit API using HTTP. This sink will ensure that the index exists (create it if it doesn't) and will append the data to the index using the same batch size as specified in the Iggy configuration."},"1774":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/quickwit-2","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/quickwit","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/quickwit#configuration","content":"url: The URL of the Quickwit server."},"1775":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/quickwit-3","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/quickwit","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/quickwit#configuration","content":"index: The index configuration using YAML, as described in the Quickwit index configuration docs"},"1776":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","type":"page","content":"Sink","breadcrumbs":["Documentation","Connectors","Sinks"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink"},"1777":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink-0","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink#overview","content":"Overview"},"1778":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink-1","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink#configuration","content":"Configuration"},"1779":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink-2","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink#environment-variable-overrides","content":"Environment Variable Overrides"},"1780":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink-3","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink#sample-implementation","content":"Sample implementation"},"1781":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink-4","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink#overview","content":"Sink connectors are responsible for writing data from Iggy streams to external systems or destinations. They provide a way to integrate Apache Iggy with various data sources and destinations, enabling data flow between Iggy and external systems."},"1782":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink-5","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink#overview","content":"The sink is represented by the single Sink trait, which defines the basic interface for all sink connectors. It provides methods for initializing the sink, writing data to external destination, and closing the sink."},"1783":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink-6","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink#configuration","content":"Each sink connector is configured in its own separate configuration file within the connectors directory specified in the main runtime config."},"1784":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink-7","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink#configuration","content":"Main runtime config (config.toml):"},"1785":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink-8","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink#configuration","content":"Sink connector config (connectors/stdout.toml):"},"1786":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink-9","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink#environment-variable-overrides","content":"Configuration properties can be overridden using environment variables. The pattern follows: IGGY_CONNECTORS_SINK_[KEY]_[PROPERTY]"},"1787":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink-10","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink#environment-variable-overrides","content":"For example, to override the enabled property for a sink with ID stdout:"},"1788":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink-11","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink#sample-implementation","content":"Let's implement the example sink connector, which will simply print the messages to the standard output."},"1789":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink-12","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink#sample-implementation","content":"Additionally, our sink connector will have its own state, which can be used e.g. to track the overall progress or store some relevant information when ingesting the data further to the external sources or tooling."},"1790":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink-13","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink#sample-implementation","content":"Also, when implementing the sink connector, make sure to use the sink_connector! macro to expose the FFI interface and allow the connector runtime to register the sink with the runtime."},"1791":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink-14","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink#sample-implementation","content":"And finally, each sink should have its own, custom configuration, which is passed along with the unique plugin ID via expected new() method."},"1792":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink-15","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink#sample-implementation","content":"Let's start by defining the internal state and the public sink connector along with its own configuration."},"1793":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink-16","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink#sample-implementation","content":"We can invoke the expected macro to expose the FFI interface and allow the connector runtime to register the sink within the runtime."},"1794":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink-17","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink#sample-implementation","content":"At a bare minimum, we need to add the following dependencies to the Cargo.toml file to compile the plugin at all:"},"1795":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink-18","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink#sample-implementation","content":"dashmap"},"1796":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink-19","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink#sample-implementation","content":"once_cell"},"1797":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink-20","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink#sample-implementation","content":"tracing"},"1798":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink-21","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink#sample-implementation","content":"Now, let's implement the Sink trait for our StdoutSink struct."},"1799":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink-22","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink#sample-implementation","content":"It's also important to note, that the supported format(s) might vary depending on the connector implementation. For example, you might expect JSON as the payload format, which can be then easily parsed and processed by upstream components such as data transforms, but at the same time, you could support the other formats and let the user decide which one to use."},"1800":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink-23","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink#sample-implementation","content":"For example, you can match against the payload enum field containing the deserialized value to process (or not) the consumed message(s)."},"1801":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink-24","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink#sample-implementation","content":"While the schema of messages (that will be consumed from the Iggy stream), cannot be controlled by the sink connector itself, the built-in configuration allows to decide what's the expected format of the messages (the particular StreamDecoder will be used)."},"1802":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink-25","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink#sample-implementation","content":"Keep in mind, that it might be sometimes difficult/impossible e.g. to transform one format to another e.g. JSON to SBE or so, and in such a case, the consumed messages will be ignored."},"1803":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink-26","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink#sample-implementation","content":"Eventually, compile the source code and create a separate connector configuration file in the connectors directory (as specified in the main runtime config.toml).  Make sure that path points to the existing plugin."},"1804":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink-27","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink#sample-implementation","content":"And that's all, enjoy using the sink connector!"},"1805":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink-28","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/sink#sample-implementation","content":"On a side note, if you'd like to produce the messages to the Iggy stream instead, you can implement your own Source connector too :)"},"1806":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/stdout","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/stdout","type":"page","content":"Stdout Sink","breadcrumbs":["Documentation","Connectors","Sinks"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/stdout"},"1807":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/stdout-0","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/stdout","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/stdout#configuration","content":"Configuration"},"1808":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/stdout-1","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/stdout","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/stdout#plugin-config-options","content":"Plugin config options"},"1809":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/stdout-2","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/stdout","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/stdout","content":"The stdout sink connector prints messages from Iggy streams to the standard output. This is useful for debugging, development, and verifying that your connector pipeline is working correctly."},"1810":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/stdout-3","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/stdout","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/stdout#plugin-config-options","content":"Option"},"1811":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/stdout-4","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/stdout","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/stdout#plugin-config-options","content":"Type"},"1812":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/stdout-5","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/stdout","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/stdout#plugin-config-options","content":"Default"},"1813":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/stdout-6","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/stdout","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/stdout#plugin-config-options","content":"Description"},"1814":{"id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/stdout-7","page_id":"/docs/connectors/sinks/stdout","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/connectors/sinks/stdout#plugin-config-options","content":"print_payload"