the domain to use for the TLS connection (default: None)"},"2138":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-17","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"tls_ca_file - the path to the CA file to use for the TLS connection (default: None)"},"2139":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-18","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"reconnection_retries - the number of retries to establish the connection (default: unlimited)"},"2140":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-19","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"reconnection_interval - the interval between the reconnection attempts (default: 1s)"},"2141":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-20","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"reestablish_after - the time to wait before reestablishing the connection (default: 5s)"},"2142":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-21","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"heartbeat_interval - the interval between the heartbeat messages (default: 5s)"},"2143":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-22","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"nodelay - whether to use the TCP_NODELAY option or not (default: false)"},"2144":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-23","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"For QUIC, the connection string is parsed with the following options:"},"2145":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-24","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"response_buffer_size - the size of the response buffer (default: 10_000_000)"},"2146":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-25","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"max_concurrent_bidi_streams - the maximum number of concurrent bidirectional streams (default: 10000)"},"2147":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-26","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"datagram_send_buffer_size - the size of the datagram send buffer (default: 100_000)"},"2148":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-27","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"initial_mtu - the initial MTU size (default: 1200)"},"2149":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-28","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"send_window - the size of the send window (default: 100_000)"},"2150":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-29","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"receive_window - the size of the receive window (default: 100_000)"},"2151":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-30","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"keep_alive_interval - the interval between the keep-alive messages (default: 5000)"},"2152":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-31","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"max_idle_timeout - the maximum idle timeout (default: 10000)"},"2153":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-32","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"validate_certificate - whether to validate the server certificate or not (default: false)"},"2154":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-33","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"reconnection_retries - the number of retries to establish the connection (default: unlimited)"},"2155":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-34","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"reconnection_interval - the interval between the reconnection attempts (default: 1s)"},"2156":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-35","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"reestablish_after - the time to wait before reestablishing the connection (default: 5s)"},"2157":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-36","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"heartbeat_interval - the interval between the heartbeat messages (default: 5s)"},"2158":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-37","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"Unless you need to provide a specific implementation of the client-side Encryptor, Partitioner or adjust some other settings, you should be good to go with the connection string. On the other hand, you can always make use of IggyClientBuilder::from_connection_string() to extend the options on top of the provided connection string."},"2159":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-38","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#connection-string","content":"Additionally, if you were to check the internal implementation of IggyClient, you'd notice that it does use IggySharedMut<> which means that you can use a single instance of the client across multiple threads. Typically, it's a good idea to create a separate connection for producing and consuming, but it's not a requirement."},"2160":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-39","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#producer","content":"The producer is a high-level abstraction that allows you to send messages to the topic. It's quite simple to use and doesn't require you to handle the offsets, partitions or any other low-level details. To begin with, you can simply invoke client.producer() to get the IggyProducerBuilder allowing you to configure the producer. Let's take a look at the basic example:"},"2161":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-40","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#producer","content":"The code above will result in creating the producer that will try to send the messages in batches of 1000 every 5 milliseconds. You can choose between the direct (an instant producer) or the background (which will send the messages in the background by buffering them). The partitioning is set to balanced which means that the producer will try to distribute the messages evenly across all the partitions. The init() method is used to ensure that the producer is ready to send the messages by validating the existence of the stream, topic etc."},"2162":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-41","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#producer","content":"Finally, you can use the send() method to send the messages to the topic. The producer doesn't need to be a mutable reference, as it's only required during the initialization phase. Here's how you can send the messages:"},"2163":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-42","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#producer","content":"Of course, you can provide the message headers, custom binary serialization etc. as it's the same Message struct as the one used in the low-level API. The producer will take care of the rest, including the retries, partitioning, batching etc."},"2164":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-43","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#consumer","content":"The consumer is a high-level abstraction that allows you to receive the messages from the topic. It's quite simple to use and doesn't require you to handle the offsets, partitions or any other low-level details. To begin with, you can simply invoke client.consumer() to get the IggyConsumerBuilder allowing you to configure the consumer. Let's take a look at the basic example:"},"2165":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-44","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#consumer","content":"The code above will result in creating the consumer that will try to consume the messages in batches of 1000 every 1 millisecond. The auto-commit is set to commit the offset every second or when all the messages are consumed (fetched). The polling strategy is set to next which means that the consumer will try to consume the next available message from the partition currently assigned to the consumer group (you can also invoke a regular consumer() builder if you do not plan to use the consumer groups). The build() method is used to create the consumer."},"2166":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-45","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#consumer","content":"Finally, you can use the next() method to receive the messages from the topic. The consumer doesn't need to be a mutable reference, as it's only required during the initialization phase. The init() is used to ensure that the consumer is ready to receive the messages by validating the existence of the stream, topic, consumer group etc.  Here's how you can consume the messages:"},"2167":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk-46","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/high-level-sdk#consumer","content":"In order to use the async iterator extension, add futures-util dependency."},"2168":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","type":"page","content":"Intro","breadcrumbs":["Documentation","SDK","Rust"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro"},"2169":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro-0","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro#high-level-vs-low-level-api","content":"High-level vs low-level API"},"2170":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro-1","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro#connection-string","content":"Connection string"},"2171":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro-2","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro#quick-example","content":"Quick example"},"2172":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro-3","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","content":"The Rust SDK is the primary and most feature-complete client for Iggy. It is available on crates.io and the source code is part of the core repository."},"2173":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro-4","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro#high-level-vs-low-level-api","content":"The SDK provides two layers:"},"2174":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro-5","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro#high-level-vs-low-level-api","content":"High-level API (recommended) - the easiest way to get started. It handles connection management, auto-batching, consumer group lifecycle, offset commits, retry logic, and reconnection out of the box. Use IggyClient, IggyProducer, and IggyConsumer for the best developer experience."},"2175":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro-6","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro#high-level-vs-low-level-api","content":"Low-level API - direct access to individual protocol operations. Useful when you need fine-grained control over every request, or when building custom abstractions on top."},"2176":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro-7","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro#high-level-vs-low-level-api","content":"The high-level API is built on top of the low-level one, so you can always drop down when needed."},"2177":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro-8","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro#connection-string","content":"The connection string is the simplest way to configure the client. It supports all four transport protocols:"},"2178":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro-9","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro#connection-string","content":"Options can be appended as query parameters:"},"2179":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro-10","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro#connection-string","content":"Personal Access Tokens are also supported:"},"2180":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro-11","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/intro#quick-example","content":"For the full getting started tutorial, see Getting Started. For the high-level producer/consumer builders, see High-level SDK and Stream Builder."},"2181":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","type":"page","content":"Stream Builder","breadcrumbs":["Documentation","SDK","Rust"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder"},"2182":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-0","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#iggystream-builder","content":"IggyStream Builder"},"2183":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-1","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#iggystreamproducer-builder","content":"IggyStreamProducer Builder"},"2184":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-2","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#producer-configuration","content":"Producer configuration"},"2185":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-3","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#iggystreamconsumer-builder","content":"IggyStreamConsumer Builder"},"2186":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-4","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#build-consumer-and-client","content":"Build consumer and client"},"2187":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-5","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#build-consumer-from-an-existing-client","content":"Build consumer from an existing client"},"2188":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-6","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#consumer-configuration","content":"Consumer configuration"},"2189":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-7","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#add-consumers-dynamically-at-runtime","content":"Add consumers dynamically at runtime."},"2190":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-8","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#add-producers-dynamically-at-runtime","content":"Add producers dynamically at runtime."},"2191":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-9","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","content":"In the previous section, the high level SDK introduced the connection string to simplify the client configuration and\nindeed, it does provide a simple way to connect to the server. However, when you write an event based application,\nyou typically encounter one or more of the following scenarios:"},"2192":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-10","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","content":"The consumer and producer operate on the same stream and topic."},"2193":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-11","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","content":"The consumer operates on different streams and topics."},"2194":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-12","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","content":"The producers operate on different streams and topics."},"2195":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-13","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","content":"Add consumers dynamically at runtime."},"2196":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-14","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","content":"Add producers dynamically at runtime."},"2197":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-15","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","content":"The stream builder provides a convenient way to create the iggy client, producer and consumer for these use cases.\nAll source code examples are located in the examples folder of the iggy repository. Also,\nif you encounter a problem with any of the examples below, please ask in the community discord."},"2198":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-16","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#iggystream-builder","content":"In the first case, the IggyStream Builder offers a fast and efficient way to get you started:"},"2199":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-17","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#iggystream-builder","content":"As you can see, the IggyStream builder is used to create the iggy client, producer and consumer.\nHere, we use the default configuration to get started quickly, but you can always customize the configuration to fit\nyour requirements."},"2200":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-18","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#iggystream-builder","content":"The consume_messages method is not part of the IggyConsumer; instead, you import the IggyConsumerMessageExt\ntrait which provides the consume_messages method. The PrintEventConsumer implements the MessageConsumer trait\nand is invoked to process each incoming message. A simple implementation is show below:"},"2201":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-19","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#iggystreamproducer-builder","content":"When you implement the producer side, you can use the IggyStreamProducer to get started:"},"2202":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-20","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#iggystreamproducer-builder","content":"If you already have a custom iggy client, you can use that one by replacing the with_client_from_url\nconstructor with the following:"},"2203":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-21","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#iggystreamproducer-builder","content":"You find sample utils to build a customized iggy client in\nthe examples folder of the iggy\nrepository."},"2204":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-22","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#producer-configuration","content":"The IggyProducerConfig gives you a way to configure the producer in sufficient detail. Please note, if you have\nquestions about any of those settings, please ask in the community discord. For basic customization, the from_stream_topic constructor\nlets you set a custom stream and topic name as well as the maximum batch size and message send interval."},"2205":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-23","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#producer-configuration","content":"The remaining configuration fields are set to default values applicable to the most common use case. This should be sufficient for a simple application, or proof of concept without getting lost in details.\nHowever, for more complex applications, you might want to configure more\ndetails and for that, see below a commented example of the full producer configuration:"},"2206":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-24","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#producer-configuration","content":"Note, when your requirements exceed this configuration, you can still\nuse the underlying low level SDK for fine grained control over every detail of the producer."},"2207":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-25","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#iggystreamconsumer-builder","content":"When you have an existing server with multiple producers, you may have to implement a consumer for a specific stream or\ntopic. In some cases you may already have a configured iggy client, in others you may need to create\none. In either case, you can use the IggyStreamConsumer to create the consumer."},"2208":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-26","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#build-consumer-and-client","content":"Similar to the previous StreamBuilder, the IggyConsumerMessageExt is used to process messages using\nthe PrintEventConsumer implementation of the MessageConsumer trait."},"2209":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-27","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#build-consumer-from-an-existing-client","content":"In the event that you have an existing iggy client, you can use the IggyStreamConsumer::build method to create the\nconsumer. To do so, just replace the with_client_from_url with the following:"},"2210":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-28","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#build-consumer-from-an-existing-client","content":"Notice, you find some utils to build a customized iggy client in\nthe examples folder of the iggy\nrepository."},"2211":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-29","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#consumer-configuration","content":"The default configuration only exists to get you started quickly i.e. to test out an idea, draft an proof of concept or\nsimilar. In practice, you often want fine grained control over the configuration. The IggyConsumerConfig gives you a way\nto configure the consumer in sufficient detail without distracting with low level details.\nPlease note, if you have questions about any of those settings, please ask in\nthe community discord. See below a commented configuration example:"},"2212":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-30","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#add-consumers-dynamically-at-runtime","content":"When you create consumers on demand at application runtime, you have to\nensure that the stream and topic exist before creating the consumer and\nyou have to set the init_retries and init_interval in the stream builder\nto ensure the consumer retries a few more times in case the topic and stream are not immediately available."},"2213":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-31","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#add-consumers-dynamically-at-runtime","content":"However, when you cannot guarantee that the stream or topic exist before the consumer starts,\nyou have to set create_stream_if_not_exists and create_topic_if_not_exists to true in the IggyConsumerConfig\nto ensure the consumer creates them and starts correctly. Other than that, you just call the\nIggyStreamConsumer::build method as before i.e.:"},"2214":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-32","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#add-consumers-dynamically-at-runtime","content":"Where get_my_custom_iggy_consumer_config refers to a function that returns an IggyConsumerConfig\nthat specifies the stream and topic to consume as well the init retry or whether to create the stream and topic."},"2215":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-33","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#add-producers-dynamically-at-runtime","content":"Adding new producers to the iggy server at runtime is as simple as creating a new config and\ncalling the IggyStreamProducer::build method. Unlike the consumer, the producer always crates\nmissing streams or topics by default. The IggyConsumerConfig has a convenient builder to create\na new configuration from just the stream, topic, batch size and send interval. See the example below."},"2216":{"id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder-34","page_id":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/sdk/rust/stream-builder#add-producers-dynamic